At 07:33 AM 1/1/2003 -0800, you wrote:
>Choice 1: Ignore it. Deny there is a problem until it gets worse. If there 
>is one thing I hate, it is a non starting engine in the morning. It's 
>cold, I need to go to work or some place else. I need a vehicle that 
>starts up when I need it and is reliable, won't break down. Does this rule 
>out this choice for everyone?

Never ignore problems......unless you like being bitten in the ass, on some
dark rainy night in the middle of no where......

>Choice 2: Replace the distributor with a 009. I read about unsatisfied 009 
>owners who want a vacuum advance distributor. I guess the 009 is now the 
>most common and easiest to buy. They come with points, rotor and cap. 
>Cost: $50 each

The .009 doesn't work well on buses UNLESS you are running dual carbs with 
insufficient vacuum to
run a vac. advance distributor.

>Choice3: Replace the points with a Pertronix igniter. They are virtually 
>trouble free. They fully function even when the distributor gets wet. (I 
>understand that Compufire igniter is not available for a single vacuum 
>advance distributor and Pertronix makes a unit though) Cost: $70 to $85

Points work fine--even better with a CDI.  Save your money for one of 
those, instead.

>Choice 4: Replace the vacuum advance distributor with a new 009 and 
>replace the points with a Petronix igniter. This spends the most money, 
>acquires the latest, easily obtainable, reliable technology. Cost: 
>Distributor($50)+Igniter($80)=Total($130)

Lots of bucks spent, but it won't run well on a bus.

>Is it pretty close of a decision for you?

Nope.  They all leave much to be desired.

>What would you recommend?

An SVDA distributor from aircooled.net.

